  "prompt": "How do dolphins use sonar?",
  "response": "Dolphins use a biological sonar system called echolocation to navigate, communicate, and hunt. Here's how it works:\n\n1. Sound Production\n- Dolphins generate high-frequency clicking sounds in their nasal passages\n- These clicks are focused through a fatty organ in their forehead called the melon\n\n2. Sound Transmission\n- The clicks are projected outward in a narrow beam\n- The sounds travel through water much faster than through air\n\n3. Sound Reflection\n- The sound waves bounce off objects in the water\n- Different surfaces and objects reflect sounds differently\n\n4. Sound Reception\n- The returning echoes are received through the dolphin's lower jaw\n- The jaw contains specialized fat that helps conduct sound to their inner ear\n\n5. Information Processing\n- Dolphins can interpret the echoes to determine:\n- Object location\n- Size\n- Shape\n- Density\n- Movement\n- Distance\n\nThis sophisticated system allows dolphins to \"see\" with sound, helping them navigate, hunt prey, and avoid obstacles in dark or murky waters. It's similar to how human-made sonar works, but much more advanced and precise.",
